Data Import

# Input older white pine plot-level data from Hatch plots

rm(list=ls())

library(nlme) 
library(ggplot2)
                  
hatch0 <- read.fwf("Hatch.dat", skip = 9, header = F, 
                   row.names = NULL, as.is = TRUE,  strip.white=T,
                   widths = c(4, 7, 8, 8, 8, 8, 8),
                   col.names = c("plot", "siteindex", "age", "NTA",
                                 "qmd", "BAA", "DHT") )                   
                   
cat("\n",nrow(hatch0)," records were read.\n",sep="") #
## 
## 173 records were read.
# omit rows of dashes and convert plot to factor variable, 
# and convert the rest to numeric

hatch <- hatch0[-which(hatch0$plot == "---"),]

hatch$plot <- as.factor(hatch$plot)
hatch$siteindex <- as.numeric(hatch$siteindex)
hatch$age <- as.numeric(hatch$age)
hatch$NTA <- as.numeric(hatch$NTA)
hatch$qmd <- as.numeric(hatch$qmd)
hatch$BAA <- as.numeric(hatch$BAA)
hatch$DHT <- as.numeric(hatch$DHT)
attach(hatch)

GLS Model

cor1 <- gls(BAA ~ age, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot))
cor2 <- gls(BAA ~ age + logNTA, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot))
cor3 <- gls(BAA ~ age + logNTA + qmd, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot))
cor4 <- gls(BAA ~ age + logNTA + qmd + DHT, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot))
cor5 <- gls(BAA ~ age + siteindex + logNTA + qmd + DHT, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot),
            data=hatch)

Removing multicolinear variables

Qualitatively, we would choose to remove QMD first, because it is a function of both NTA and BAA. But well test out all the options before making a decision.

Rebuilding model 5 without DHT improves the AIC

gls_no_DHT <- gls(BAA ~ age + siteindex + logNTA + qmd, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot),
                  data=hatch)
gls_no_NTA <- gls(BAA ~ age + siteindex + qmd + DHT, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot),
                  data=hatch)
gls_no_age <- gls(BAA ~ siteindex + logNTA + qmd + DHT, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot),
                  data=hatch)
gls_no_QMD <- gls(BAA ~ age + siteindex + logNTA + DHT, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot),
                  data=hatch)

AIC(gls_no_DHT, gls_no_NTA, gls_no_age, gls_no_QMD, cor5)

I choose to remove both DHT and QMD for the following reasons: DHT has not been significant in any of the models built thus far, and QMD has a very large VIF score, indicating that its highly multicolinear with other predictors.

Final gls model

The residuals look okay. It seems that the GLS model is not properly accounting for the varying distribution of residuals between plots, so lets try building a mixed-effect LME

gls_final <-  gls(BAA ~ age + siteindex + logNTA, corr=corCAR1(form = ~ age | plot),
                  data=hatch)

LME Model

#model with all covariates
lme1 <- lme(BAA ~ age + siteindex + logNTA + qmd + DHT, random = ~ 1 + age | plot,
            data=hatch)

#model with same covariates as the GLS model
lme2 <- lme(BAA ~ age + siteindex + logNTA, random = ~ 1 + age | plot, data=hatch)

AIC

Removing insignificant variables

Remove DHT because it is not significant.

lme3 <- lme(BAA ~ age + siteindex + logNTA + qmd, random = ~ 1 + age | plot, data=hatch)

Removing multicolinear variables

The AIC does just as well when removing the insignificant DHT, but the VIF still indicates that QMD is highly covariate (VIF > 5). Because of this covariance, we also remove it from the model and result in the same model structure as the GLS.

AIC and VIF

AIC(lme3)
## [1] 1069.7
round(car::vif(lme3), 2)
##       age siteindex    logNTA       qmd 
##      1.49      1.32      4.61      5.91

Comparison between GLS and LME

The LME random-effects model better accounted for the longitudinal data. This can be seen by the more equal residual variance in the residual by plot boxplots, and in the more evenly distributed residuals in the residual vs.fitted plot. The residual vs.fitted plot also shows that the LME model better fits the data because the residuals are closer to zero.

The AIC for the GLS was 1155, while the AIC for the LME was 1177. This is because the LME introduces more degrees of freedom. The AIC is not a foolproof test of best model in this case, as the lowest AIC model clearly has heteroskedasticity between plots.

require(ggalt)
## Loading required package: ggalt
hatch$lmeresid <- resid(lme2)
hatch$glsresid <- resid(gls_final)

lme2bp <- ggplot(data=hatch, aes(x=plot, y=lmeresid))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_point(size=0.4)+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(title="LME residual distribution", subtitle="Blue boxplots indicate abnormal residual distribution")+
  ylab("Residuals")+
  geom_boxplot(data=subset(hatch, plot %in% c("90", "4", "48", "52", "60", "73")),
               color="blue")

cor4bp <- ggplot(data=hatch, aes(x=plot, y=glsresid))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_point(size=0.4)+
  theme_bw()+
  ggtitle("GLS residual distribution")+
  ylab("Residuals")+
  geom_boxplot(data=subset(hatch, plot %in% c("3", "48", "51", "40", "43", "60", "73"
                                              , "90", "45", "61", "79", "80")),
               color="blue")

multiplot(lme2bp, cor4bp)

  geom_point(size=0.7)+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE)+
  theme_bw()+
  ggtitle("LME residual plot")+
  xlab("Fitted")+
  ylab("Residuals")+
  geom_encircle(data=subset(hatch, lmeresid>40), s_shape=0.05, expand= 0, color="blue")+
  geom_encircle(data=subset(hatch, lmefitted > 360), s_shape=0.05,
                expand= 0.08, color="blue")+
  geom_point(data=subset(hatch, lmeresid>40), color="blue", size=0.7)+
  geom_point(data=subset(hatch, lmefitted > 360), color="blue", size=0.7)+
  annotate("text", x= 295, y= 59, label="Plot 90", color="blue")+
  annotate("text", x=315, y= -33, label="Plot 90", color="blue")
